uard and Joyce Jacobsen write, have fostered a new era in higher education, and institutions must know how to respond.For many higher education observers and participants, including most administrators and faculty, the maze of legal mandates and potential risks can seem bewildering. Guard, a general counsel with years of higher education law experience, and Jacobsen, a former college president, map this unfamiliar terrain. All the Campus Lawyers provides a vital, up-to-date assessment of the impact of legal concerns on higher education and helps readers make sense of the most pressing trends and issues, including civil rights; free speech and expression; student life and wellness; admissions, advancement, and community relations; governance and oversight; the higher education business model; and on-campus crises, from cyberattacks to pandemics.As well as informing about the latest legal and regulatory developments affecting higher education, Guard and Jacobsen offer practical guidance to those in positions of campus authority. There has never been a more crucial time for college and university boards, presidents, inside and outside counsel, and other higher education leaders to know the law and prepare for legal challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCollege studentsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aLawyerszUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxAdmissionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Educational Law & Legislation.2bisacsh  aFERPA.  aaccessibility.  aaffirmative action.  acovid 19.  adisability.  adiversity.  aeconomics.  aequity.  agreek life.  aharassment.  ahazing.  alegacy.  aliability.  amental health.  aoperations.  